use in my research, in my book.

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:09.850
First of all, we must acknowledge
that there is a historical link

00:04:09.850 --> 00:04:12.440
between language and identity.

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:14.560
Okay? I think we can
all agree on that.

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:17.290
Many, many studies done on that.

00:04:17.290 --> 00:04:20.930 position:56%
But I would like to clarify that
the book addresses more the identity

00:04:20.930 --> 00:04:24.690
that is our ethnic
or national identity.

00:04:24.690 --> 00:04:28.380
And just to clarify, what I mean
by identity is it's the sense

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:30.210
of belonging to some group.

00:04:30.210 --> 00:04:34.890
What we feel we are
or where we belong.

00:04:34.890 --> 00:04:39.520
Okay? We must also agree, or
we may agree, or we may know,

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:43.410
that language may be a
core value in cultures.

00:04:43.410 --> 00:04:46.470
Okay? Culture is transmitted
through language.

00:04:46.470 --> 00:04:51.500
So, it is essential, okay, and
is linked to culture as well.

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:53.410
Attitudes about languages.

00:04:53.410 --> 00:04:56.180
The book has to do a
lot with attitudes.

00:04:56.180 --> 00:05:01.040 position:56%
So, it, we, you know, attitudes
about languages are assessments made

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:03.820
about the value of a
particular language.

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:06.490
They can be either positive
or negative attitudes,

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:08.900
and that is very important,

00:05:08.900 --> 00:05:13.080
because that influences
the outcome of a language.

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:17.430
A language can be born, a language
can also die because of attitudes.

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:20.960
So, if we have positive attitudes,
that means that we respect,

00:05:20.960 --> 00:05:23.660
we admire, we preserve
the language, we use it.

00:05:23.660 --> 00:05:27.230
If we don't, then that
means that we don't use it.

00:05:27.230 --> 00:05:28.530
That we don't preserve it.

00:05:28.530 --> 00:05:33.650
That we don't respect
it and it might die out.

00:05:33.650 --> 00:05:37.610
We must also assume that
attitudes are not static.

00:05:37.610 --> 00:05:40.100
Okay? They are changing constantly

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:43.190
because of our surrounding
circumstances.

00:05:43.190 --> 00:05:46.830
So, we must assume that
they can or should change,

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:50.830
and language policy must
take that into account.

00:05:50.830 --> 00:05:54.980
Prevalent language attitudes
provide social indicators

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:56.660
of changing beliefs.

00:05:56.660 --> 00:05:58.310
Okay? They're like the thermometer.

00:05:58.310 --> 00:05:59.730
They're taking the temperature.

00:05:59.730 --> 00:06:01.170
What's going on?

00:06:01.170 --> 00:06:02.470
Okay? Are we-- ?

00:06:02.470 --> 00:06:04.870
Is it because we're in war?

00:06:04.870 --> 00:06:06.620
Is it because we're in peace?

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:07.920
Times of peace, times of war.

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:09.220
I mean, what's going on?

00:06:09.220 --> 00:06:11.520
Why is it changing?

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:15.670
Nowadays, the need to confront
and eradicate negative attitudes

00:06:15.670 --> 00:06:17.850
and stereotypes may
actually be leading us away

00:06:17.850 --> 00:06:22.320
from that traditional stance
of one language, one identity.

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:26.740
Okay? So, times are a changing,
although, if we go back in history,

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:28.160
that's what everybody
said at the time

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:29.460
that they were learning, as well.

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:32.800
A lot of transformation going on.

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:34.100
All right.

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:36.620
So, continuing, some
