00:06:38.710 --> 00:06:42.720
So, I'm going to try to
summarize in a nut shell a little

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:45.330
about the history of Puerto Rico
and why we have these two languages

00:06:45.330 --> 00:06:47.460
on our island, because we
have Puerto Rican Spanish

00:06:47.460 --> 00:06:49.610
and we have American English.

00:06:49.610 --> 00:06:50.910
All right?

00:06:50.910 --> 00:06:52.980
Now, we also have what we
call the Hispanicisation

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:55.470
and Americanization processes

00:06:55.470 --> 00:06:59.900
and they have affected attitude
towards both attitudes towards

00:06:59.900 --> 00:07:03.150
those languages.

00:07:03.150 --> 00:07:06.370
So, Hispanicisation process
began when the Spaniards arrived

00:07:06.370 --> 00:07:08.930
on the island in the
fifteenth century.

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:11.170
They colonized the
island, they were--

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:14.650
they brought their own varieties
of Spanish from the Canary Islands,

00:07:14.650 --> 00:07:19.760
from the Andalusian area of
Spain, which is to the south.

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:22.430
They had different varieties.

00:07:22.430 --> 00:07:27.020
They had to reach a
common ground in language.

00:07:27.020 --> 00:07:31.620
They were greeted by the indigenous
population that already existed

00:07:31.620 --> 00:07:34.120
on the island, the Taino.

00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:37.320
And, basically, decimated the
Taino population [laughter].

00:07:37.320 --> 00:07:41.940
But, you know, some did run for the
hills, okay, and they did survive.

00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:43.240
Some of them did.

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:47.240
We still have DNA of the
Taino in Puerto Ricans.

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:50.690
So, they didn't really influence
the language all that much.

00:07:50.690 --> 00:07:53.320
But, we do have place
names that exist today

00:07:53.320 --> 00:07:54.830
that come from their language.

00:07:54.830 --> 00:07:57.800
We also have the Africans,
the slaves that were brought

00:07:57.800 --> 00:08:00.580
to our island in the
sixteenth century,

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:03.150
and they also had their
own languages.

00:08:03.150 --> 00:08:06.690
They came mostly from the
West coast, the Gold Coast.

00:08:06.690 --> 00:08:11.730
They Uribi, the Igbo, people
were the ones who were more--

00:08:11.730 --> 00:08:15.360
the ones that arrived the most.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:19.280
And so, their languages
also had influence

00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:21.830
on this emerging new
variety of Spanish

00:08:21.830 --> 00:08:23.940
which is known as Puerto
Rican Spanish.

00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:26.300
And also, the new and
emerging people known

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:27.880
as the Puerto Rican people.

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:33.750 position:56%
Okay? So, we're a lovely mixture of
many beautiful people and languages.

00:08:33.750 --> 00:08:35.320
And that's Puerto Rican Spanish,

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:40.450
400 years of Puerto Rican
Spanish evolving on the island,

00:08:40.450 --> 00:08:44.060
creating a link to identity
for the Puerto Ricans.

00:08:44.060 --> 00:08:45.870
And then-- that was 400 years--

00:08:45.870 --> 00:08:50.420
and then, we had the
Spanish-American War, where,

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:54.590
as part of the aftermath of
that, Spain handed Puerto Rico

00:08:54.590 --> 00:08:58.690
over to the U.S. and
that was in 1898.

00:08:58.690 --> 00:09:02.380
And so, it's been about
118, 119 years since then.

00:09:02.380 --> 00:09:06.300
The U.S., once they
arrived, immediately said,

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:08.680 position:56%
Spain is out, U.S. is in [laughter].

00:09:08.680 --> 00:09:13.570
Okay? So, now, you're
going to speak English.

00:09:13.570 --> 00:09:16.530
And everything is going
to be the way we do it.

00:09:16.530 --> 00:09:18.960
Okay? So, that's how it was.

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:22.260
So, the attitudes then, where we
have the positive attitude towards

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:27.170
Spanish, because this is what
we have known for 400 years,

00:09:27.170 --> 00:09:30.580
then became a negative
attitude towards English

00:09:30.580 --> 00:09:32.760
because it's being imposed.

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:34.630
It wasn't a choice.

00:09:34.630 --> 00:09:37.640
It was today you speak--
yesterday you spoke Spanish,

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:38.940 position:56%
today you're going to speak English.

00:09:38.940 --> 00:09:42.010
And schools are in English,
government is in English,

00:09:42.010 --> 00:09:44.650
holidays are ours,
everything is ours.

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:48.480
And what you did before
doesn't count anymore.

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:51.240 position:56%
So, this is where we stand nowadays.

00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:52.540
Attitudes are changing.

00:09:52.540 --> 00:09:55.700
I just wanted you to know this
